 (38,10,'Javascript',1,1,'<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>JS Switch</li>\r\n<li>JS Popup Boxes</li>\r\n<li>JS Functions</li>\r\n<li>JS For Loop</li>\r\n<li>JS While Loop</li>\r\n<li>JS Break Loops</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Learning Target</h2>\r\n<h2>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use multiple selections using switch selection structure.</h2>\r\n<h2>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use for and do/while repetition structures to execute statements in a program repeatedly.</h2>\r\n<h2>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use the break and continue program control statements.</h2>\r\n<h2>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use the logical operators.</h2>\r\n<h2>Discussion</h2>\r\n<h2>The switch Multiple-Selection Structure</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; JavaScript provides the switch multiple-selection structure to handle a series of decisions in which a variable or expression is tested separately for each of the values it may&nbsp; assume and different actions are taken.</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The switch structure consists of a series of case labels and an optional default case. When the flow of control reaches the switch structure, the controlling expression in the parentheses following keyword switch is evaluated. The value of this expression is compared with the value of the case labels, starting with the first case label. If a match occurs, the statements for that case are executed. If no match occurs between the controlling expression&rsquo;s value and the value in case label, the statements in the default case execute.</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The break statement at the end of a case causes control to immediately exit the switch. The break statement is not required for the last case in the switch structure ( or the default case when it appears last) because program control automatically continues with the next statement after the switch structure.</h2>\r\n<h2>The general format of switch selection structure:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; switch (<em>variable</em>)</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; case&nbsp;<em>n</em>:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; statement;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; break;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>A sample program using switch structure:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>The for Repetition Structure</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The for repetition structure handles all the details of counter-controlled repetition.</h2>\r\n<h2>Counter-controlled repetition requires:</h2>\r\n<h2>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The&nbsp;<em>name&nbsp;</em>of a control variable (or loop counter).</h2>\r\n<h2>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The&nbsp;<em>initial value</em>&nbsp;of the control variable.</h2>\r\n<h2>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The&nbsp;<em>increment (or decrement)&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;by which the control variable is modified each time through the loop ( also known as&nbsp;<em>&nbsp;each iteration of the loop).</em></h2>\r\n<h2>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The condition that tests for the&nbsp;<em>final value</em>&nbsp;of the&nbsp; control variable to determine whether looping should continue.</h2>\r\n<h2>The general format of for repetition structure:</h2>\r\n<h2>for (&nbsp;<em>initialization; loopContinuationTest; increment</em>&nbsp;)</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; statement;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Sample expression:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>for ( var counter=1; counter &lt;=7; ++counter)</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; document.writeln ( &ldquo;The value of counter is&rdquo; +counter);</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Sample program</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A script that displays the value of the counter in ascending order.</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Another sample program</h2>\r\n<h2>A script that displays the value of the counter in descending order and compute for the total value of the counter.</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>The do/while Repetition Structure</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The do/while repetition structure is similar to the while structure. In the while structure, the loop-continuation condition is tested at the beginning of the loop before the body of the loop is performed.</h2>\r\n<h2>The do/while structure test the loop-continuation condition after the loop is performed.; therefore,&nbsp;<em>the loop body is always executed at least once.</em></h2>\r\n<h2>Note: It is necessary to use braces in the do/while structure even if there is only one statement in the body. This is required to avoid confusion.</h2>\r\n<h2>The general format of do/while structure:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; do</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; {</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Statement;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; } while (condition);</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Sample do/while structure program:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>The break and continue Statements</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The break and continue statements alter the flow of control. The break statement, when executed in a while, for, do/while or switch structure, causes the immediate exit from that structure.</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The continue statement, when executed in a while, for or do/while structure, skips the remaining statements in the body of that structure and proceeds with the next iteration of the loop. In while and do/while structures, loop-continuation test is evaluated immediately after the continue statement is executed. In the for structure, the increment expression is executed, then the loop-continuation test is evaluated.</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Sample program for break statement:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Sample program using continue statement:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2><em>&nbsp;</em></h2>\r\n<h2><em>&nbsp;</em></h2>\r\n<h2><em>.</em>The labeled break and continue Statements</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The break statement can break out of an immediately enclosing while, for, do/while or switch structure. To break out&nbsp; of a nester set of structures, you can use the&nbsp;<em>labeled&nbsp;</em><em>break&nbsp;</em><em>statement.&nbsp;</em>This statement, when executed in a while, for, do/while or switch, causes immediate exit from that structure and any number of enclosing repetition structures; program execution resumes with the first statement after the enclosing&nbsp;<em>labeled statement.</em></h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The continue statement proceeds with the next iteration (repetition) of the immediately enclosing while, for or do/while structure. The&nbsp;<em>labeled&nbsp;</em><em>continue&nbsp;</em><em>statement,&nbsp;</em>when executed in a repetition structure (while, for or do/while), skips the remaining statements in that structure&rsquo;s body and any number of enclosing repetition structures, then proceeds with the next iteration of the enclosing&nbsp;<em>labeled repetition structure(</em>&nbsp;a repetition structure preceded by a label.</h2>\r\n<h2>Sample labeled break statement:</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Sample program using&nbsp;<em>labeled continue statements:</em></h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>The Logical Operators</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; JavaScript provides&nbsp;<em>logical operators&nbsp;</em>that may be used to form more complex conditions by combining simple conditions. The logical operators are &amp;&amp; (<em>logical AND), || ( logical OR)&nbsp;</em><em>and&nbsp;</em><em>!(logical NOT,&nbsp;</em><em>also called&nbsp;</em>logical negation).</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Table 13.1&nbsp; Truth table for the &amp;&amp; (logical AND) operator.</h2>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>Expression 1</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>Expression2</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"208\">\r\n<h2>Expression1&amp;&amp;expression2</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"208\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>True</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"208\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>True</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"208\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>True</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<h2>True</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"208\">\r\n<h2>True</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Table 13.2 Truth table for the || (logical OR) operator.</h2>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"107\">\r\n<h2>Expression1</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"107\">\r\n<h2>Expression2</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"216\">\r\n<h2>Expression1 || expression 2</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"107\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"107\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"216\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"107\">\r\n<h2>False</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"107\">\r\n<h2>True</h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"216\">\r\n<h2>