 (65,17,'Matrix Theory',0,0,'<p><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">A set&nbsp;</span><i style=\"font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\">is continuous</i><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">&nbsp;=def (and this is a&nbsp;</span><i style=\"font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\">very rough</i><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">&nbsp;definition!!)</span></p><p style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\"></p><ol type=\"i\" style=\"margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 20px; font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\"><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">it is dense<p><i style=\"font-size: 14px;\">and</i></p><p></p></li><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">it has no \"gaps\".</li></ol><p style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\"></p><ul style=\"margin-left: 20px; font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\"><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">So<ul style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">The real number line is continuous.</li><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">It is sometimes called \"the&nbsp;<b style=\"font-size: 16px;\">continuum</b>\" (pronounced /con-tin-you-um/).</li><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">In fact, some mathematicians define a continuous set as just the real numbers.</li></ul><p></p></li><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">There are lots of formal ways to define the continuum; here`s one:<p></p><ul style=\"font-size: 16px;\">A totally-ordered set is continuous =def any nonempty subset that has an upper bound also has a least upper bound.</ul><p>Here`s what this means:</p><p></p><ul style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Consider the real number line.<br>Locate  on it.&nbsp;<br>Now consider the set of all numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;.&nbsp;<br>Some upper bounds of this set are: , 3.1415926536, 3.15, 3.2, 4, 4.1, 4.10938571023987, etc.&nbsp;<br>However, the&nbsp;<i style=\"font-size: 16px;\">smallest</i>&nbsp;(i.e., the \"least\") of these upper bounds is .&nbsp;<br>If we had been considering the subset of&nbsp;<i style=\"font-size: 16px;\">rationals</i>&nbsp;that are&nbsp;&nbsp;,<ul style=\"font-size: 16px;\">then  would&nbsp;<i style=\"font-size: 16px;\">not</i>&nbsp;be a member of this subset (because it`s not a rational).</ul>But if the subset is continuous, then &nbsp;<i style=\"font-size: 16px;\">is</i>&nbsp;a member.<p>I.e., continuous sets have no gaps.</p></ul><p></p></li><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">The reals are not countable.<p></p></li><li style=\"font-size: 16px;\">The study of continuous sets is&nbsp;<i style=\"font-size: 16px;\">not</i>&nbsp;part of discrete math.</li></ul>');
